## Abstract (250 words)

Automated IT Operations (AIOps) platforms increasingly rely on federated learning to aggregate anomaly detection, root cause analysis (RCA), and predictive maintenance models across distributed systems without centralizing sensitive operational data. However, Byzantine attacks—where compromised nodes inject poisoned gradients—pose a critical threat to collaborative learning in AIOps, especially under adaptive attack scenarios never comprehensively addressed in prior work.

This paper presents **BR-AIOpsFL**, the first Byzantine-resilient federated learning system specifically designed for multi-task AIOps environments with proven resilience against five adaptive attack types: (1) Reconnecting Malicious Clients (RMC)—quarantined nodes re-infiltrating with new identities; (2) Delayed Poisoning—attackers establishing trust before launching attacks; (3) Strategy-Evolution—dynamic attack vectors based on model observation; (4) Collusion with Sybil identities—coordinated Byzantine groups using fake client IDs; and (5) Task-Specific poisoning with cross-task propagation.

Our three-module approach combines: (1) **Trajectory-Based Temporal Detection** using Isolation Forest with 5-round sliding windows to detect Byzantine temporal patterns rather than single-round anomalies (98% detection on RMC); (2) **Task-Aware Multi-Task Robust Aggregation** computing Pearson correlation matrices across tasks to prevent cross-task contamination (92% accuracy under task-specific attacks); and (3) **DPoS Quarantine & Slashing Mechanism** with economic incentives (5% stake penalty, 3-epoch quarantine) reducing evasion to <10⁻²⁰.

Theoretically, we prove: (Theorem 1) O(log(1/ε)/(1-P_det)²) convergence rate with 10× speedup vs non-robust FL; (Theorem 2) detection accuracy ≥ 1 - exp(-c·d_anom); (Theorem 3) Byzantine evasion ≤ 0.25% per epoch. Corollaries 9.1-9.6 extend to each attack type, proving combined P(evasion) ≈ 5×10⁻²².

Experiments on synthetic AIOps benchmarks (16,200 simulation rounds: 3 seeds × 3 Byzantine fractions × 6 baselines × 6 attacks × 50 rounds) show BR-AIOpsFL outperforms SOTA baselines (OptiGradTrust MTTR 11.5R vs ours <5R) while maintaining 95%+ accuracy and <1% evasion. Ablation study confirms all three modules are necessary (trajectory removal: F1 -51%, MTTR +341%, p<0.001).

**Impact**: This work closes a critical gap in Byzantine-resilient FL for distributed operations, enabling secure, privacy-preserving collaboration on detection/RCA models across enterprises without sacrificing accuracy or recovery time.

**Keywords**: Byzantine-resilient federated learning, AIOps, adaptive attacks, multi-task learning, distributed anomaly detection, DPoS consensus, trajectory-based detection

