## 3. System Model & Threat Model

### 3.1 Federated Learning Setup

**Participants**:
- N clients (monitoring agents, edge nodes, branch offices) i ∈ [N]
- 1 trusted aggregator (central coordinator)
- M federated tasks j ∈ [M] (anomaly detection, RCA, forecasting)

**Data & Learning**:
- Client i holds local dataset D_i (operational metrics from site i)
- Task j has parameters w^j ∈ ℝ^d (shared globally)
- Each round r, client i computes gradient ∇L_i^j(w_r^j) on local data
- Aggregator computes weighted average: w_{r+1}^j ← w_r^j - η Σ_i c_i ∇L_i^j(w_r^j) / N
- Multi-task learning: Shared encoder + task-specific heads enable cross-task gradient mixing (realistic AIOps: CPU/memory/latency features shared)

### 3.2 Byzantine Threat Model

**Threat Assumptions**:
- Up to B ≤ 0.4N clients are Byzantine (compromised)
- Byzantine clients can:
  - Observe current global model w_r (synchronous FL)
  - Submit arbitrary gradients g_i (not from SGD on local data)
  - Coordinate with other Byzantine clients (no communication limit among Byzantine nodes)
  - Spawn Sybil identities (fake client IDs)
- Honest clients compute gradients correctly but may become compromised after training (restart possible → RMC attack vector)

### 3.3 AIOps Metrics & Success Criteria

**Operational Goals**:
- Model accuracy >92% (AIOps SLA baseline)
- MTTR <30 minutes (5-10 rounds @ 1 round/min)
- Alert precision >85% (reduce alert fatigue)
- RCA success rate >90%

**Security Goals**:
- Byzantine detection F1 >0.90
- Evasion rate <5% (% Byzantine escaping detection)
- Convergence not poisoned (final model utility maintained)

